		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Mar 24th 2:26 PM2005 </span><span class="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1111658303157143285&num=16&page=0&post=1&replyto=1111692700240439249"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1111692700240439249></a></small>| <span id="fs8">Edited: 2005-03-24 14:32:19</span></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=180319"><span id="Scholar">rickea</span></a><b><span id="Scholar"><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />500 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.04]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=rickea&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>I have played EQ for about 3 years (have 2 accounts as my daughter likes to play with me sometimes) and a couple weeks ago was given W0W by a client of mine who plays with one of his co-workers. <br /> <br />Although I had planned to wait until after tax season to load WoW, my daughter finally drove me nuts and I installed it for her last week. She plays a lot and I have played some as well. <br /> <br />My impressions so far: <br /> <br />1. WoW is a fun game but more geared towards the ps2 crowd from what I can see. As someone mentioned, the graphics are nice but rather cartoonish (though the opening credits are great). In the little I have been on (boy does WOW have server problems LOL never complain about SOE again*), the other players and chatter appear to much more juvernile than I am used to on EQ. <br /> <br />2. WoW is much more geared towards the casual player than EQ as well as more solo oriented (while grouping can speed things up, in Wow you can solo to your heart's content and progress nearly as fast or even faster given 3 below). WoW has interesting quests than lead you farther a field, but each area is a lot like the old EQ newbie areas with ever higher level mobs - my level 17 pally (reached after maybe 8 hours of play btw) is currently getting about 4-5% per kill tackling 18th to 20th lv Dark Iron Dwarves (and easily completed a quest at 15 requiring killing 2 17th levels together). <br /> <br />3. EQ groups tend to last a significant amount of time and you often group with the same people your level as you progress over months, in WoW the average group lasts just as long as it takes one person to reach their individual goal (once had 3 of us in a mini dungeon when 1 of us got the 10th mob kill and promptly left, 2 kills later the other one said she had her's and good luck LOL). You also have interesting loot options in that coins split but group leader can designate loot rules for items (my daughter was in a group of 5 where group leader designated himself as only looter and then disbanded the group when he ran out of room - of course no split for rest). I also was in a group with a level 20 warlock who kept dying against orcs and recruited a 28 pally to help us but pally was doing tradeskills and 20 minutes later still had not bothered to come join us. <br /> <br />4. WoW does offer a nice progression of quests (all of which are soloable if you wait a few levels) and you get experience for finding new areas which then show up in your map (your position is always marked on the maps). GM response time is very good in WoW and the flying rides are super. However, the quests don't require the level of work in EQ and don't seem to have the same level of accomplishment from my prospective. <br /> <br />5. Death - Wow does not have any experience loss for death and CRs are really non existant in that you become a ghost and can run back to your corpse (marked on the map btw) and nothing can touch you until you resurect yourself (at 1/2 health and mana but with all equipment). You equipment does that damage and eventually dying a lot will require spending some silver to repair. <br /> <br />6. PVP element is well done in WoW with allied territory, contested territory (where anyone is fair game) and enemy territory. <br /> <br />Long post, quick read is that Wow plays more like a PS2 game and EQ more like a PC version of the same game. <br /> <br />Overall I prefer EQ, but notice my 12 year old is hooked on Wow. <br /> <br />Edit <br /> <br />* Forgot my footnote - Wow is very unstable platform in that server wide crashes are a daily occurance (once happened 3 times in 1 day for us) with sometimes a several hour wait for it to come back - shattered hand where I play seems to be down even when most aren't btw. Also, there is a maximum number allowed per server and if more want to join, they have to wait until other people log off - while this is often less than 10 minutes when it occurs, I did have to wait over 20 minutes on Palm Sunday. There also is no warning of a coming crash, what happens is that the npcs tend to disappear, you can't interact with anyone (though you can still run around or move into another zone) and then about 3 or 4 minutes later you are bounced out. When you come back, you are back where you were before the server started to crash (not where you ran to). <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Thu Mar 24 14:37:36 2005 by rickea</span></i></p>
