<p><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />EQ2 is certainly pretty but it lacks freedom and, more importantly, it lacks soul.<hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br />A very good observation. SoE seems to have taken all the things that were problems in EQ and spent so much time making sure they can't happen in EQ2 (and failing) that the cure is worse than the problem ever was. And even with high-end hardware it lagged very badly at crucial moments. <br /> <br />And they keep making fundamental changes to the game which mean that suddenly your class choice is nonsense or your abilities are reset.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /> <br />WoW is much more fun and Blizzard seem to have got the right idea about gameplay being more important than ultimate graphics quality. I like WoW graphics but they are just texture fills mostly. However that doesn't matter if the overall effect is good and the game is enjoyable. <br /> <br />I've not yet had a server crash in WoW and hardly any lag except in Ironforge (a major city). They can handle massively greater loads of people in a zone than EQ or EQ2 and there are virtually no zonings, the world is simply enormous. <br /> <br />Their quest structure is good as it has logical reasons for doing things and helps you track what you are doing. And it is progressive and continuous.  <br /> <br />And you can quite happily play WoW as PvE <img border="0" src="/shared/smilies/smile.gif" alt="icon"/> <br /> <br />WoW has now reached 500,000 concurrent players (1.5m subscribers) which I believe is higher than EQ where I'd heard 450,000 concurrent as a maximum. <br /> <br />EQ is still better for group play and raiding. And I prefer EQ graphics to EQ2 graphics.</p>
